<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT/DTA-466 Diesel Engine Service (1990) - CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND SLEEVES - PISTON &#38; ROD
        ASSEMBLY REMOVAL - REMOVAL
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="6">
        <title>REMOVAL</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Loosen the connecting rod bolts using a socket and breaker-bar,
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150604">6.4</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                .
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the bolts, by hand. Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150605">6.5</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                .
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The bolts should turn out of the connecting rod freely. If binding exists, check thread
                        condition carefully.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the connecting rod cap and bearing insert. Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150606">6.6</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                .
            </para>
            <figure id="ef4150604" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg11553" filename="../figcg1/CG11553.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.4. Loosen Connecting Rod Bolts.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef4150605" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg11554" filename="../figcg1/CG11554.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.5. Remove Bolts by Hand.</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="ef4150606" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="cg11555" filename="../figcg1/CG11555.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6.6. Remove the Connecting Rod Cap and Bearing Insert.</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the upper connecting rod bearing insert by carefully inserting a small screwdriver at
                the edge of the bearing insert (between the connecting rod and the crankshaft journal) to release the
                tang. Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150607">6.7</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                .
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>BE CAREFUL NOT TO SCRATCH THE CRANKSHAFT JOURNAL.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Push the connecting rod up slightly to release pressure on the bearing insert. Slide the
                insert around the crankshaft journal and remove. Refer to
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150608">6.8</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                .
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>With the connecting rod bearings removed, tape the halves together to form a circle. Mark the
                        tape to indicate the cylinder location. This will aid during bearing inspection.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the piston and connecting rod assemblies as follows:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Push the piston and rod assembly from the cylinder bore using a wood or plastic handle.
                    Once the piston rings are free of the cylinder bore, the assembly can be removed from the top of the
                    crankcase. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4150609">6.9</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    .
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Rotate the engine and remove all of the remaining pistons as outlined. Be sure to
                    replace each bearing cap on its respective connecting rod after removal of the piston from the
                    engine.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Identify the connecting rod and piston assemblies upon removal so they can be
                    reinstalled in their respective cylinder bores.
                </para>
                <figure id="ef4150607" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11556" filename="../figcg1/CG11556.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.7. Release Bearing Insert Tang.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150608" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11557" filename="../figcg1/CG11557.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.8. Remove Bearing Insert.</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4150609" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11558" filename="../figcg1/CG11558.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.9. Remove Piston and Connecting Rod Assembly.</caption>
                </figure>
            </step2>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
